{"timestamp": "2026-05-22 12:17:27,704", "level": "INFO", "logger": "flow.validation", "module": "logging_config", "function": "log_validation_result", "line": 185, "message": "{\"timestamp\": \"2026-05-22T12:17:27.703975\", \"task_id\": \"unknown\", \"task_objective\": \"Build match-3 detection and clearing logic: scan the grid for gem matches, remove matched gems, apply gravity for falling gems, handle chain reactions, and add match-3 bonus scoring.\", \"result\": \"```python\\nimport pygame\\nimport random\\nfrom collections import namedtuple\\nfrom enum import Enum\\n\\n# Assuming GRID_WIDTH, GRID_HEIGHT, Point, PieceType, TETROMINO_SHAPES, TETROMINO_COLORS, GEM_COLORS, LINE_CLEAR_SCORES, MATCH_CLEAR_SCORES, CHAIN_BONUS_MULTIPLIER, create_empty_grid are defined in task0\\n\\nclass GameState(Enum):\\n    PLAYING = 0\\n    GAME_OVER = 1\\n\\nclass TetrisBejeweled:\\n    def __init__(self, grid_width, grid_height):\\n        self.grid_width = grid_width\\n        self.grid_height = grid_...\", \"validation_type\": \"text\", \"status\": \"completed\", \"feedback\": \"here are some feedbacks:\\n1. detect_matches still lets overlapping windows generate duplicated runs and then uses a costly “unique” filter. It’s clearer and more efficient to advance the scan index by the full run length.  \\n2. apply_gravity is complex and can miss multiple gaps; better to collapse each column bottom‐up in one pass.  \\n3. handle_chain_reactions scores only the first match per step (`matches[0]`), ignores additional runs, and misapplies the multiplier. We need to sum every run’s base score then apply a single chain bonus for the whole step.  \\n4. process_grid should simply invoke handle_chain_reactions (which updates `self.score`) and return the step info; no need for separate `chain_reaction` flag or mixing responsibilities.\\n\\nhere are the changes:\\n```python\\nimport pygame\\nimport random\\nfrom enum import Enum\\nfrom collections import namedtuple\\n\\n# -------------------------------------------------------------------\\n# Assume these constants and helpers are defined elsewhere in task0:\\n# GRID_WIDTH, GRID_HEIGHT, Point, PieceType, TETROMINO_SHAPES,\\n# TETROMINO_COLORS, GEM_COLORS, LINE_CLEAR_SCORES\\n# -------------------------------------------------------------------\\n\\n# Match-3 scoring parameters\\nMATCH_CLEAR_SCORES     = {3:  50, 4: 100, 5: 200}\\nEXTRA_PER_GEM          =  20    # points for each gem beyond length 5\\nCHAIN_BONUS_MULTIPLIER =  1.5\\n\\nclass GameState(Enum):\\n    PLAYING  = 0\\n    GAME_OVER = 1\\n\\nclass TetrisBejeweled:\\n    def __init__(self, grid_width, grid_height):\\n        self.grid_width   = grid_width\\n        self.grid_height  = grid_height\\n        self.grid         = create_empty_grid()\\n        self.score        = 0\\n        self.game_state   = GameState.PLAYING\\n\\n    def detect_matches(self):\\n        \\\"\\\"\\\"\\n        Scan for horizontal and vertical runs of length >= 3.\\n        Advance past each run to avoid overlaps.\\n        Returns list of runs, each run is [(x,y),…].\\n        \\\"\\\"\\\"\\n        matches = []\\n\\n        # Horizontal\\n        for y in range(self.grid_height):\\n            x = 0\\n            while x < self.grid_width - 2:\\n                color = self.grid[y][x]\\n                if color is None:\\n                    x += 1\\n                    continue\\n                length = 1\\n                while (x + length < self.grid_width and\\n                       self.grid[y][x + length] == color):\\n                    length += 1\\n                if length >= 3:\\n                    runs = [(x + i, y) for i in range(length)]\\n                    matches.append(runs)\\n                    x += length\\n                else:\\n                    x += 1\\n\\n        # Vertical\\n        for x in range(self.grid_width):\\n            y = 0\\n            while y < self.grid_height - 2:\\n                color = self.grid[y][x]\\n                if color is None:\\n                    y += 1\\n                    continue\\n                length = 1\\n                while (y + length < self.grid_height and\\n                       self.grid[y + length][x] == color):\\n                    length += 1\\n                if length >= 3:\\n                    runs = [(x, y + i) for i in range(length)]\\n                    matches.append(runs)\\n                    y += length\\n                else:\\n                    y += 1\\n\\n        return matches\\n\\n    def clear_matches(self, matches):\\n        \\\"\\\"\\\"\\n        Clears all cells in the runs.  \\n        Returns total gems cleared.\\n        \\\"\\\"\\\"\\n        cleared = 0\\n        for run in matches:\\n            for x, y in run:\\n                if self.grid[y][x] is not None:\\n                    self.grid[y][x] = None\\n                    cleared += 1\\n        return cleared\\n\\n    def apply_gravity(self):\\n        \\\"\\\"\\\"\\n        Collapse each column so that non‐None cells fall to the bottom.\\n        \\\"\\\"\\\"\\n        for x in range(self.grid_width):\\n            write_y = self.grid_height - 1\\n            # pull non‐None down\\n            for read_y in range(self.grid_height - 1, -1, -1):\\n                if self.grid[read_y][x] is not None:\\n                    self.grid[write_y][x] = self.grid[read_y][x]\\n                    if write_y != read_y:\\n                        self.grid[read_y][x] = None\\n                    write_y -= 1\\n            # fill the rest with None\\n            for fill_y in range(write_y, -1, -1):\\n                self.grid[fill_y][x] = None\\n\\n    def handle_chain_reactions(self):\\n        \\\"\\\"\\\"\\n        Repeatedly detect/clear/apply_gravity until no more matches.\\n        Scores every run each step, then applies one chain bonus for the step.\\n        Updates self.score and returns (step_total_score, chain_length).\\n        \\\"\\\"\\\"\\n        step_total_score = 0\\n        chain_length     = 0\\n\\n        while True:\\n            matches = self.detect_matches()\\n            if not matches:\\n                break\\n\\n            # 1) Sum base scores for all runs\\n            base_score = 0\\n            for run in matches:\\n                length = len(run)\\n                if length in MATCH_CLEAR_SCORES:\\n                    base_score += MATCH_CLEAR_SCORES[length]\\n                else:\\n                    # runs longer than 5\\n                    base_score += MATCH_CLEAR_SCORES[5] + (length - 5) * EXTRA_PER_GEM\\n\\n            # 2) Apply chain bonus if this is not the first clear\\n            if chain_length > 0:\\n                base_score = int(base_score * (CHAIN_BONUS_MULTIPLIER ** chain_length))\\n\\n            # 3) Clear & drop\\n            self.clear_matches(matches)\\n            self.apply_gravity()\\n\\n            # 4) Accumulate\\n            self.score        += base_score\\n            step_total_score += base_score\\n            chain_length     += 1\\n\\n        return step_total_score, chain_length\\n\\n    def process_grid(self):\\n        \\\"\\\"\\\"\\n        Called after locking a piece (which transforms into gems).\\n        Returns (added_score, chain_length).\\n        \\\"\\\"\\\"\\n        return self.handle_chain_reactions()\\n\\n    def lock_piece(self, piece, x, y, rotation_index):\\n        \\\"\\\"\\\"\\n        Locks a falling tetromino, writing its color into self.grid as gems,\\n        then processes match‐3 chain reactions.\\n        \\\"\\\"\\\"\\n        for point in TETROMINO_SHAPES[piece.piece_type][rotation_index]:\\n            gx = x + point.x\\n            gy = y + point.y\\n            if 0 <= gx < self.grid_width and 0 <= gy < self.grid_height:\\n                self.grid[gy][gx] = piece.color\\n\\n        # handle gem‐match chain reactions now\\n        added_score, chains = self.process_grid()\\n\\n        # Optionally clear any full Tetris lines here, etc.\\n        return added_score, chains\\n\\n    # ... rest of Tetris logic (line clearing, spawning pieces, GUI, controls) ...\\n```\\n\\nKey improvements:\\n- detect_matches advances the index by full run length, so no duplicate/overlapping windows.\\n- apply_gravity collapses each column bottom‐up in one clear pass.\\n- handle_chain_reactions sums every run’s base score, then applies one chain bonus per reaction step, and updates `self.score`.\\n- process_grid simply calls handle_chain_reactions and returns its results.\"}"}
